text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eucalyptus distuberosa was first formally described in 2009 by Dean Nicolle and the description was published in the journal Nuytsia from a specimen he collected in 2000 north-east of Yellowdine. The specific epithet (distuberosa) is derived from the Latin words dis meaning "without" or "not" and tuberosus meaning "full of lumps", referring to the lack of a lignotuber in this species.There are two subspecies recognised by the Australian Plant Census:

Eucalyptus distuberosa subsp. aerata that has prominently ribbed buds and fruit;
Eucalyptus distuberosa subsp. distuberosa that lacks ornamentation on the buds and fruit, although intermediates are known.
